WEBVTT

00:02.835 --> 00:05.670
♪ Boy, the way                  
Glenn Miller played ♪           

00:05.672 --> 00:09.340
             ♪ Songs that made  
             The hit parade ♪   

00:09.342 --> 00:13.011
♪ Guys like us                  
We had it made ♪                

00:13.013 --> 00:16.280
    ♪ Those were the days ♪     

00:16.282 --> 00:20.284
               <i>♪ And you knew</i>   
           <i>Where you were then ♪</i>

00:20.286 --> 00:23.622
 <i>♪ Girls were girls</i>             
 <i>And men were men ♪</i>             

00:23.624 --> 00:30.394
  <i>♪ Mister, we could use a man</i>  
   <i>Like Herbert Hoover again ♪</i>  

00:30.396 --> 00:33.031
 <i>♪ Didn't need</i>                  
 <i>No welfare state ♪</i>             

00:33.033 --> 00:36.534
             <i>♪ Everybody pulled</i> 
             <i>His weight ♪</i>       

00:36.536 --> 00:40.872
     <i>♪ Gee, our old LaSalle</i>     
           <i>Ran great ♪</i>          

00:40.874 --> 00:46.678
♪ Those were the days ♪         

00:53.252 --> 00:54.252
 And just remember one thing -  

00:54.254 --> 00:55.620
when you're out there tomorrow, 

00:55.622 --> 00:57.722
     you're fishing with me     
        and my buddies,         

00:57.724 --> 01:01.459
    let's have no talk about    
 politics or world conditions,  

01:01.461 --> 01:02.994
  or anything dumb like that.   

01:02.996 --> 01:05.830
          Keep it all fish talk.

01:05.832 --> 01:07.231
Don't worry, Arch.              

01:07.233 --> 01:10.101
I promise I won't say anything  
to offend your peer group.      

01:10.103 --> 01:14.739
    What do you mean, "pier"?   
    We're fishing off a boat.   

01:14.741 --> 01:16.041
I forgot.                       

01:16.043 --> 01:18.309
Hey, Arch. Didn't you say       
the bluefish were running?      

01:18.311 --> 01:19.610
             That's what I said.

01:19.612 --> 01:21.512
The line you've got on there    
is too heavy.                   

01:21.514 --> 01:23.314
Shouldn't you be using          
a 25-pound line?                

01:23.316 --> 01:26.051
              Nah. 25-pound line
            breaks too easy.    

01:26.053 --> 01:28.286
Yeah. But with a 40-pound line, 
it's not fair.                  

01:28.288 --> 01:29.721
It's not the sporting           
thing to do.                    

01:29.723 --> 01:31.355
         Ah, listen to this guy.

01:31.357 --> 01:32.891
                    If I use    
                a 25-pound line,

01:32.893 --> 01:34.826
              can you hear what 
             the fish would say?

01:34.828 --> 01:36.027
                "Oh, Jeez.      
            I love this hook.   

01:36.029 --> 01:38.997
            "There's a sport    
        at the other end of it."

01:38.999 --> 01:43.334
Arch, you're not giving         
the fish a fighting chance.     

01:43.336 --> 01:44.936
        I don't want to fight   
            with the fish,      

01:44.938 --> 01:47.238
        I want to catch them.   

01:47.240 --> 01:48.740
I'm gonna use                   
the lighter line.               

01:48.742 --> 01:50.308
                You do what     
                 you want to do.

01:50.310 --> 01:52.110
You know, Arch, I'm really      
looking forward to tomorrow.    

01:52.112 --> 01:53.945
I think we're gonna             
have a lot of fun.              

01:53.947 --> 01:55.180
          Yeah. You bet we will.

01:55.182 --> 01:56.581
                I want to tell  
             you something else.

01:56.583 --> 01:58.216
          It makes me very happy

01:58.218 --> 02:00.819
you're doing something normal   
     for a change like fishing. 

02:00.821 --> 02:03.188
    Up to now, it's been nothing
    but books and bedrooms.     

02:03.190 --> 02:06.424
              Here. Hold the end
            of this now, huh?   

02:06.426 --> 02:10.995
  Oh. I hate to interrupt you   
  while you're being friends.   

02:10.997 --> 02:14.099
              Then why don't you
                leave us alone? 

02:14.101 --> 02:15.499
    All I want to know          

02:15.501 --> 02:19.403
  is what do my two fisherboys  
      want to eat tonight?      

02:19.405 --> 02:22.941
                I think the word
            for it is dinner.   

02:22.943 --> 02:24.743
  Tonight you've got a choice.  

02:24.745 --> 02:26.477
          You can have          
      yesterday's chicken       

02:26.479 --> 02:28.880
      or the day before's       
        meatloaf.               

02:28.882 --> 02:31.116
     And you can have them      
          hot or cold.          

02:31.118 --> 02:33.985
 You can have the meatloaf cold 
      and the chicken hot,      

02:33.987 --> 02:36.387
      or the chicken cold       
     and the meatloaf hot.      

02:36.389 --> 02:41.259
      Or you can have them      
     both hot or both cold.     

02:48.934 --> 02:50.034
                 Well, I think--

02:50.036 --> 02:53.037
        Or you can have         
    tomorrow's liver today.     

02:53.039 --> 02:56.808
              Why don't you just
            surprise us, huh?   

02:56.810 --> 02:59.210
EDITH: Hello, Gloria.           

02:59.212 --> 03:00.444
MICHAEL: Hi, honey.             

03:00.446 --> 03:02.480
How was your                    
day at work?                    

03:02.482 --> 03:04.448
                         Fine.  
That's good.                    

03:04.450 --> 03:05.850
Do you want                     
to eat here tonight             

03:05.852 --> 03:07.551
or are you and Mike             
gonna go out?                   

03:07.553 --> 03:08.920
                I don't know.   

03:08.922 --> 03:10.922
Honey, if you want to go out    
it's all right.                 

03:10.924 --> 03:11.956
                I don't care.   

03:11.958 --> 03:13.357
Good.                           

03:13.359 --> 03:15.359
I figure we're getting up       
early to go fishing tomorrow,   

03:15.361 --> 03:16.795
we might as well                
stay home, huh?                 

03:16.797 --> 03:18.663
            Whatever you say.   

03:18.665 --> 03:20.665
            Gloria,             
    are you all right?          

03:20.667 --> 03:21.800
Yeah.                           

03:21.802 --> 03:23.334
                You're acting   
                  kind of funny.

03:23.336 --> 03:26.404
Oh, I'm sorry.                  
I won't do it again.            

03:26.406 --> 03:31.276
    Gloria, would you like      
to help me get the dinner on?   

03:31.278 --> 03:32.443
        Sure, Ma.               

03:32.445 --> 03:34.045
 What are you sitting there for?

03:34.047 --> 03:35.914
              You waiting to get
              your picture took?

03:35.916 --> 03:38.316
         Go on. Help your mother
            get the dinner on.  

03:38.318 --> 03:39.818
              Will you hurry up?
                  I'm hungry.   

03:39.820 --> 03:42.086
             [SOBS]             

03:43.755 --> 03:45.423
            Gloria,             
    what's the matter?          

03:45.425 --> 03:47.458
                 Leave me alone!

03:47.460 --> 03:49.393
Why did you even                
say that to her?                

03:49.395 --> 03:53.164
             What? I didn't hear
             myself say nothing.

03:54.766 --> 03:56.000
      Where is Gloria?          

03:56.002 --> 03:58.903
    Oh, gee, she's upstairs     
      crying her eyes out.      

03:58.905 --> 04:01.172
     Oh, my. What happened?     

04:01.174 --> 04:02.440
            I don't know.       

04:02.442 --> 04:05.043
        I told her to go on in  
      and help you set the table

04:05.045 --> 04:06.344
     and the waterworks started.

04:06.346 --> 04:09.480
Oh. Something's                 
bothering her.                  

04:09.482 --> 04:11.182
She put me in mind of you       

04:11.184 --> 04:14.652
    when you was going          
      through the change.       

04:14.654 --> 04:19.656
      Oh, Archie, I think       
she's too young for that.       

04:21.861 --> 04:23.828
        Gee, thanks for         
  straightening me out, Edie.   

04:24.997 --> 04:26.164
        Whatever it is,         

04:26.166 --> 04:27.565
 this is your fault, this here. 

04:27.567 --> 04:29.533
      You should've talked      
    to her about this.          

04:29.535 --> 04:32.670
 How could I when I didn't know 
      it was gonna happen?      

04:32.672 --> 04:34.939
  I'm talking about years ago.  

04:34.941 --> 04:36.341
    You should've took          
      your daughter aside.      

04:36.343 --> 04:38.709
  You should've said, "Gloria,  
    there are gonna be times    

04:38.711 --> 04:40.511
    "when you're gonna          
     be a pain in the neck      

04:40.513 --> 04:41.946
    "and you're gonna           
    upset your father.          

04:41.948 --> 04:44.148
      Don't ever do that."      

04:44.150 --> 04:46.217
         Oh, all right.         

04:46.219 --> 04:47.485
    [FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]     

04:47.487 --> 04:49.053
  Oh, she's coming back down.   

04:49.055 --> 04:51.856
All right, shush. Make out like 
you didn't notice nothing.      

04:51.858 --> 04:55.526
I'm glad you're back. Do you    
feel all right now, Gloria?     

04:55.528 --> 04:56.861
             Oh, yeah,          
          she's fine, Ma.       

04:56.863 --> 04:58.629
    I'm sorry I acted           
        that way.               

04:58.631 --> 05:00.098
    Oh, think nothing of it,    
          little girl.          

05:00.100 --> 05:02.166
  Nobody here noticed nothing,  
         did we, Edie?          

05:02.168 --> 05:04.635
  No. I was out in the kitchen  
    when it happened.           

05:04.637 --> 05:07.838
     You told me about it.      

05:09.574 --> 05:11.175
Gloria, dear, do you            
feel all right enough           

05:11.177 --> 05:12.576
to help me                      
with the dinner?                

05:12.578 --> 05:13.978
 Sure, Ma.                      

05:13.980 --> 05:16.014
    What's the story? What's the
    matter with your wife?      

05:16.016 --> 05:18.416
I don't know.                   
 How'd you get her to come down?

05:18.418 --> 05:19.951
    I just asked her.           

05:19.953 --> 05:22.287
She said, "I'll come down.      
There's nothing wrong with me." 

05:22.289 --> 05:23.721
  Something's depressing her.   

05:23.723 --> 05:26.190
     Oh, well, that's very      
     simple to understand.      

05:26.192 --> 05:27.558
MICHAEL: What?                  

05:27.560 --> 05:29.894
     Don't you know nothing     
      about women at all?       

05:29.896 --> 05:31.562
 When they're down in the dumps 
        this way,               

05:31.564 --> 05:34.265
    you wanna cheer them up,    
    you buy them a new hat.     

05:34.267 --> 05:37.368
Gloria doesn't wear hats.       

05:37.370 --> 05:41.439
 Maybe that's what's the matter 
with her. She wants a hat.      

05:43.275 --> 05:45.810
    Go buy her a hat.           
    I'll lend you the money.    

05:45.812 --> 05:47.045
         That's not it.         

05:47.047 --> 05:51.950
         Dinner! Get it         
        while it's cold.        

05:51.952 --> 05:56.054
    Gee, what a joke.           
    Serve it up, huh?           

05:56.056 --> 05:58.990
     Gloria, have some meatloaf,
        it's delicious.         

05:58.992 --> 06:00.158
     I'm not                    
     hungry.                    

06:00.160 --> 06:01.592
        All right, over here,   
              then, over here.  

06:01.594 --> 06:04.262
        What's the matter,      
                Gloria?         

06:04.264 --> 06:06.497
    I don't know, Ma.           
    I just feel blah.           

06:06.499 --> 06:09.934
    Well, you felt all right    
  this morning when you left.   

06:09.936 --> 06:13.037
    Yeah. I was fine until      
    I got on the subway tonight.

06:13.039 --> 06:14.405
Did somebody                    
bother you?                     

06:14.407 --> 06:16.341
Oh, gee, some of them animals   
        on the subway,          

06:16.343 --> 06:18.376
                they ought to   
                  be chained up.

06:18.378 --> 06:19.610
         It's nothing like that.

06:19.612 --> 06:21.446
             Listen, if I was   
         the mayor of this city,

06:21.448 --> 06:23.481
                  I'd quarantine
                them subways.   

06:23.483 --> 06:25.383
How would people                
get to work?                    

06:25.385 --> 06:28.019
              Let them eat cake.

06:29.654 --> 06:31.055
Gloria, tell me                 
what happened.                  

06:31.057 --> 06:33.224
                 Well, I was    
            feeling good, I was.

06:33.226 --> 06:35.293
              I was glad it was 
            the end of the week.

06:35.295 --> 06:37.528
  I was really looking forward  
        to coming home.         

06:37.530 --> 06:40.465
  Anyway, I got on the subway,  
          I sat down,           

06:40.467 --> 06:42.533
      and I began to look       
     at the faces around me     

06:42.535 --> 06:46.070
 and they all looked the same,  
        dull and blank.         

06:46.072 --> 06:48.606
 And all of a sudden I thought, 
    "What's the use?"           

06:48.608 --> 06:53.511
All you need, little girl,      
 is a good dose of castor oil.  

06:53.513 --> 06:54.612
             What?              

06:54.614 --> 06:55.813
         That's right.          

06:55.815 --> 06:57.081
Any time I ever come home       

06:57.083 --> 06:58.483
          with my tail          
      dragging behind me,       

06:58.485 --> 06:59.884
          that's what           
     my mother done to me.      

06:59.886 --> 07:01.919
She'd grab me by the nose,      
    open up the kisser          

07:01.921 --> 07:04.155
        and a good dose         
      right down the pipe.      

07:04.157 --> 07:06.657
    Boy, that cheered me up     
          every time.           

07:08.660 --> 07:11.329
Castor oil                      
cheered you up?                 

07:11.331 --> 07:16.167
  Damn right. It was either be  
cheered up or get another dose. 

07:16.169 --> 07:20.071
Gloria, maybe it'll help you if 
you talk about it a little more.

07:20.073 --> 07:21.739
                What's there    
                  to talk about?

07:21.741 --> 07:24.142
    It's just there's nothing   
          to look forward to.   

07:24.144 --> 07:28.012
Oh, Gloria, you've got          
your whole life ahead of you    

07:28.014 --> 07:29.480
and you've got Mike.            

07:29.482 --> 07:33.317
     Oh, gee, she's feeling bad 
    enough. Don't make it worse.

07:33.319 --> 07:34.352
        Stop with that.         

07:34.354 --> 07:35.786
                Oh, nuts to you.

07:35.788 --> 07:38.489
Eat something, Gloria.          
 You'll feel better.            

07:38.491 --> 07:42.226
It's just that it's always      
 the same thing day after day.  

07:42.228 --> 07:43.928
      It's all so useless.      

07:43.930 --> 07:45.963
Hey, Gloria, honey,             
I know how you feel.            

07:45.965 --> 07:47.731
Sometimes I hate                
my day too.                     

07:47.733 --> 07:49.934
You realize how many            
boring things I gotta do        

07:49.936 --> 07:51.835
in a single day                 
that drive me crazy?            

07:51.837 --> 07:54.138
I gotta get up,                 
I gotta brush my teeth,         

07:54.140 --> 07:55.940
I have to shave                 
and I hate to shave.            

07:55.942 --> 07:58.842
There are mornings when I stand 
there debating with that mirror,

07:58.844 --> 08:02.213
"Should I shave or should I     
cut my throat?" but I shave.    

08:02.215 --> 08:06.451
     You know, it's too bad     
 you always lose that argument. 

08:06.453 --> 08:09.620
I'm talking to Gloria. Will you 
lay off with the stupid remarks?

08:09.622 --> 08:10.854
                 It's my table--
You're not helping.             

08:10.856 --> 08:12.423
We've got a problem.            
                 Don't tell me--

08:12.425 --> 08:14.692
      That's another thing      
    that's always the same,     

08:14.694 --> 08:17.728
the two of you arguing and      
  always about the same thing.  

08:17.730 --> 08:20.131
     Nothing every changes      
     in this crummy house.      

08:20.133 --> 08:21.466
            What do you mean,   
                "crummy house"? 

08:21.468 --> 08:22.800
                Where do you get
                that stuff?     

08:22.802 --> 08:24.268
    Gloria, that ain't nice.    

08:24.270 --> 08:27.638
 Your father and me have always 
 tried to give you a good home. 

08:27.640 --> 08:30.808
Yeah. But it's always the same, 
     every night the same.      

08:30.810 --> 08:32.643
      "How was your day?"       
            "Lousy."            

08:32.645 --> 08:34.145
 The same, "What's for dinner?" 

08:34.147 --> 08:35.413
The same, "Get me a beer."      

08:35.414 --> 08:37.715
Is that all life's about?       
        Excuse me.              

08:37.717 --> 08:40.683
Wait a minute. You ain't getting
  away with that, little girl.  

08:40.686 --> 08:42.186
Come on, now.                   

08:42.188 --> 08:44.188
This ain't                      
no royal palace here.           

08:44.190 --> 08:47.158
Me and your mother              
ain't no duke or dukess.        

08:49.661 --> 08:51.895
But I think                     
we've done pretty good.         

08:51.897 --> 08:54.298
      Not in my book you didn't.
Well, just what do you mean?    

08:54.300 --> 08:56.367
Ooh!                            
    What is this here?          

08:56.369 --> 09:01.405
Gloria feels upset. I'm sure she
 don't mean what she's saying.  

09:01.407 --> 09:04.175
Yes, I do! Don't you understand?

09:04.177 --> 09:06.877
      I don't wanna end up      
      like the two of you!      

